	bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, https://dblp.org},
	abstract = {In this paper, we analyze the clash between privacy-oriented cryptocurrencies and emerging legal frameworks\xa0for combating financial crime, focusing in particular on the recent European Union regulations. We analyze Monero, a leading “privacy coin” and a major point of concern for crime-fighters, and\xa0study the scope of due diligence that must be exercised under the new\xa0law with regard to Monero trading platforms and how it translates to\xa0the technical capabilities of the Monero protocol. We both recognize flaws in the legislation and identify technical pitfalls threatening either the effective compliance of, say, Monero exchanges or\xa0the anonymity endeavour of Monero itself. Of independent interest\xa0is that we turn to anamorphic cryptography (marking one of the\xa0first practical applications of the concept) and leverage it to build\xa0a hidden transaction layer embedded in the Monero blockchain\xa0that obfuscates illegal money flow and circumvents transaction-level attempts at enforcing the EU law.}
