	abstract = {Key Mismatch Attacks (KMA) pose a significant threat\xa0to lattice-based key encapsulation mechanisms (KEMs), such\xa0as CRYSTALS-Kyber (Kyber), standardized as NIST FIPS 203. Despite advancements in KMA, including multi-positional strategies\xa0and enhanced oracles like the Multi-Value Key Mismatch Oracle (MV-KMO), existing methods suffer from high query counts and detectable ciphertexts, limiting their practicality. This paper proposes techniques to enhance KMA efficiency and stealth against Kyber\xa0and Saber. First, for CPA-secure KEMs, we propose a multi-bit inference strategy that uses crafted ciphertexts to extract information\xa0about multiple private key coefficients per Key Mismatch Oracle\xa0(KMO) query, reducing the required queries for Kyber1024 from 2368 to\xa02268 and for FireSaber from 2623 to 2571. Second, for CCA-secure KEMs,\xa0we present a minimal-query KMA method leveraging the Hamming Weight Incremental (HWI) leakage model to recover the full decapsulated message, thereby reducing queries from 2176 to 12 for Kyber1024\xa0and from 2433 to 16 for FireSaber. Third, we develop a stealthy\xa0KMA variant for CCA-secure KEMs that reconstructs the noise vector\xa0to recover the private key, generating ciphertexts statistically indistinguishable from legitimate ones, as confirmed by entropy\xa0and Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence analyses. These advancements improve KMA performance and covertness, revealing critical vulnerabilities in lattice-based KEMs and informing future cryptographic defenses.}
}


